<%- include('../../partials/header') %>

<style>
    .explainer-header { text-align: center; padding: 60px 20px 20px 20px; }
    .explainer-header h1 { font-size: 3em; color: var(--white); margin-bottom: 10px; line-height: 1.2; }
    .explainer-header h1 span { color: var(--gold); text-shadow: 0 0 15px var(--glow-gold); }
    .explainer-header p { color: var(--silver); font-size: 1.15em; max-width: 800px; margin: 15px auto 40px auto; line-height: 1.6; }

    .content-wrapper { max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto 60px auto; padding: 0 20px; }
    
    .explainer-box { background-color: var(--dark-gray); border: 1px solid #333; border-radius: 15px; padding: 40px; margin-bottom: 40px; box-shadow: 0 10px 30px rgba(0,0,0,0.3); }
    .explainer-box h2 { color: var(--gold); font-size: 1.8em; margin-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 1px solid #333; padding-bottom: 10px; display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 15px; }
    .explainer-box p { color: var(--silver); line-height: 1.7; font-size: 1.05em; margin-bottom: 20px; }

    /* Layout for Text + Lottie */
    .text-image-split { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 250px; gap: 40px; align-items: center; }
    
    /* Code Highlights Grid */
    .code-grid { display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(300px, 1fr)); gap: 20px; margin-top: 30px; }
    .code-card { background-color: var(--black); border: 1px solid #444; border-left: 4px solid var(--red); padding: 20px; border-radius: 8px; transition: transform 0.2s, border-color 0.3s; display: flex; flex-direction: column; }
    .code-card:hover { transform: translateY(-5px); border-left-color: var(--gold); box-shadow: 0 5px 15px rgba(255, 215, 0, 0.1); }
    
    .code-card-header { display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; margin-bottom: 15px; }
    .code-platform { font-size: 0.75em; font-weight: bold; padding: 3px 8px; border-radius: 12px; color: var(--black); }
    .code-platform.android { background-color: var(--android-color); }
    .code-platform.ios { background-color: var(--white); }
    .code-platform.windows { background-color: var(--windows-color); color: var(--white); }
    .code-platform.all { background-color: var(--silver); }

    .code-card code { display: block; background: #222; color: #ffadad; padding: 10px 12px; border-radius: 5px; font-family: monospace; font-size: 0.95em; margin-bottom: 15px; border: 1px solid #333; word-wrap: break-word; }
    .code-card h4 { color: var(--white); margin-bottom: 10px; font-size: 1.1em; }
    .code-card p { color: #aaa; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0; line-height: 1.6; flex-grow: 1; }

    .trust-banner { background: rgba(46, 204, 113, 0.1); border: 1px solid var(--green); padding: 30px; border-radius: 12px; text-align: center; margin-top: 50px; box-shadow: 0 0 20px rgba(46, 204, 113, 0.1); }
    .trust-banner h3 { color: var(--green); margin-bottom: 15px; font-size: 1.5em; }

    @media (max-width: 768px) {
        .text-image-split { grid-template-columns: 1fr; text-align: center; }
        .text-image-split lottie-player { margin: 0 auto; }
        .explainer-header h1 { font-size: 2.2em; }
        .explainer-box { padding: 25px; }
    }
</style>

<main>
    <div class="explainer-header">
        <div class="container">
            <h1>Understanding <span>Antivirus Detections</span></h1>
            <p>Why do safe mods sometimes get flagged by security software like VirusTotal? Learn the science behind "False Positives" and how to read scan results like a pro.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="content-wrapper">
        
        <!-- Section 1: What is a False Positive? -->
        <div class="explainer-box">
            <h2><i class="fas fa-search-shield"></i> What is a False Positive?</h2>
            <div class="text-image-split">
                <div>
                    <p>When software developers create an application, they lock it with an encrypted "Digital Signature." To create a working mod (like unlocking premium features or adding a mod menu), our developers must decompile the app, modify the code, and repackage it without that original lock.</p>
                    <p>Modern Antivirus (AV) scanners are strictly designed to flag <strong>any file that has had its original signature broken or altered</strong>. Because modding fundamentally alters the code structure, highly sensitive AV engines will automatically flag the file as "suspicious," even if the modification is 100% safe. This is known in the cybersecurity industry as a <strong>False Positive</strong>.</p>
                </div>
                <!-- ✅ UPGRADE: Professional Lottie Animation instead of broken image -->
                <lottie-player src="/animations/shield.json" background="transparent" speed="1" style="width: 250px; height: 250px; filter: drop-shadow(0 0 15px var(--glow-gold));" loop autoplay></lottie-player>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 2: Common Scary Codes -->
        <div class="explainer-box">
            <h2><i class="fas fa-bug"></i> Common "Scary" Codes Explained</h2>
            <p>If a mod receives 3 or 4 flags on VirusTotal, don't panic! Look closely at the <strong>names</strong> of the detections. If you see variations of the codes below, they are harmless flags caused entirely by the modding process.</p>
            
            <div class="code-grid">
                
                <!-- Android Signature Flags -->
                <div class="code-card">
                    <div class="code-card-header">
                        <h4>Public Signature Flag</h4>
                        <span class="code-platform android">Android</span>
                    </div>
                    <code>Android.Riskware.TestKey.rA<br>PUA.AndroidOS.ApkSignatureKiller</code>
                    <p><strong>Meaning:</strong> The original Google Play developer signature was removed. To make the mod installable, the creator used a public "Test Key" to re-sign it. Antiviruses flag this simply to inform you that the app wasn't signed by the original corporate developer.</p>
                </div>

                <!-- Android PUP Flags -->
                <div class="code-card">
                    <div class="code-card-header">
                        <h4>Unwanted Program (PUP)</h4>
                        <span class="code-platform android">Android</span>
                    </div>
                    <code>PUP/Android.Malct.1151236<br>PUP/Android.Moda.1297228</code>
                    <p><strong>Meaning:</strong> "PUP" stands for Potentially Unwanted Program. This is a generic, low-level heuristic warning. It is typically triggered by modified premium features, integrated ad-blockers, or floating cheat menus that behave differently than a standard app.</p>
                </div>

                <!-- iOS Dylib/Memory Injection Flags -->
                <div class="code-card">
                    <div class="code-card-header">
                        <h4>Dylib Injection (False Trojan)</h4>
                        <span class="code-platform ios">iOS / macOS</span>
                    </div>
                    <code>OSX/GM.Stealer.KK<br>OSX.Trojan.Agent.ELJ669<br>MacOS:Agent-BDU [Susp]</code>
                    <p><strong>Meaning:</strong> iOS mods rely on "Dylib Injection" to bypass App Store sandboxes and unlock features. Because the tweak actively hooks into the app's memory to change its behavior, aggressive scanners mistake this code injection for a "Stealer" or "Trojan." It is a classic false positive.</p>
                </div>

                <!-- Windows Patch Flags -->
                <div class="code-card">
                    <div class="code-card-header">
                        <h4>License Bypass Flag</h4>
                        <span class="code-platform windows">Windows</span>
                    </div>
                    <code>HackTool:Win32/Patch<br>Crack.Activator</code>
                    <p><strong>Meaning:</strong> The mod contains scripts designed to bypass premium license checks or DRM verifications. The AV flags it as a "HackTool" because it circumvents copyright protections, not because it damages your PC.</p>
                </div>

            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 3: How GPL Mods Protects You -->
        <div class="trust-banner">
            <h3><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> The GPL Mods Safety Guarantee</h3>
            <p style="color: var(--white); margin: 0; line-height: 1.6; font-size: 1.05em;">
                We don't just rely on automated scanners. Files marked with our <strong><span style="color: var(--gold);">✔ Certified</span></strong> badge have been manually audited by our administration team. Furthermore, our community-driven <strong>"Working Vote"</strong> system ensures that if a file genuinely causes issues, our thousands of daily users will flag it instantly.
            </p>
        </div>

    </div>
</main>

